1. What is GitHub and why is it important for developers?

GitHub serves as the central hub for code collaboration, hosting 120M+ repositories and 100M+ developers. It's mandatory for job applications (95% of tech roles require GitHub profiles).

Core Value Proposition:


No GitHub → Isolated code → No collaboration → Career limitation
With GitHub → Portfolio + Teamwork + Open Source → Job offers

Final-year project multiplier: GitHub README + Demo Video = 10x interview callbacks.



2. What is a repository in GitHub?

Repository (repo) = Complete project folder with code, history, issues, documentation:


my-streamlit-crud-app/
├── app.py                 # Main Streamlit app
├── employees.db           # SQLite database  
├── requirements.txt       # Dependencies
├── README.md             # Project documentation
└── .github/workflows/    # CI/CD pipeline

Repo Types:

| Public               | Private                 | GitHub Pages                |
| -------------------- | ----------------------- | --------------------------- |
| PortfolioOpen source | Team projectsCompany IP | Live demoyourname.github.io |



3. How does GitHub help in team-based development?

GitHub enables parallel development through branches, pull requests, code review:


Main Branch (stable) ← Pull Request ← Feature Branch (experiment)
                    ↑ Review + Test ↑ Code changes
                    ↑ Merge        ↑ Multiple developers

Production Team Flow:


graph TD
    A[Developer A: auth.py] --> B[Create PR #23]
    C[Developer B: Reviews] --> D[CI Tests Pass]
    E[Team Lead: Approves] --> F[Merge to main]
    F --> G[Deploy to Streamlit Cloud]

Collaboration Features:

    Pull Requests: Code review + discussion

    Issues: Bug tracking + feature requests

    Projects: Kanban boards

    Actions: Automated testing/deployment



4. What is the difference between Git and GitHub?

| Git                                   | GitHub                           |
| ------------------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Command-line toolgit commit, git push | Web platformHosts Git repos      |
| Local version control                 | Cloud collaboration              |
| Free, open-source                     | Freemium SaaS                    |
| git clone                             | https://github.com/username/repo |

Relationship: GitHub = Git + Web UI + Collaboration.



5. How does GitHub help in tracking code changes?

GitHub visualizes complete change history with commit graph, blame view, diff comparison:


Commit History:
commit abc123 → "Add bcrypt auth" → +45/-2 lines
commit def456 → "Fix SQL injection" → +12/-8 lines
commit ghi789 → "Deploy to Streamlit" → +3/-1 lines

Tracking Features:


🔍 File blame → "Who changed line 42?"
⏪ Revert → Undo entire commit
📊 Contribution graph → Weekly commits
🔀 Compare branches → See all differences

Streamlit Project Tracking Example:


Week 1: README + Basic CRUD → 5 commits
Week 2: Authentication → 8 commits  
Week 3: Forgot password → 12 commits
Week 4: Deploy + Polish → 20 commits ✓

Production GitHub Workflow Template

bash
# 1. Clone project
git clone https://github.com/yourname/streamlit-crud-app.git
cd streamlit-crud-app

# 2. Create feature branch
git checkout -b feature/auth-system

# 3. Make changes + commit
git add .
git commit -m "Add bcrypt authentication + forgot password"

# 4. Push + Create PR
git push origin feature/auth-system
# → GitHub creates Pull Request automatically

